Author: Jacky Barraza¶

Notebook 3.2/3.3¶

Its time to build and train propensity models exploring tecniques to deal with unbalaced datasets and test the algoriths selected on the first aproach

The algorithms decided to test on this section are:

LogisticRegression
DecisionTreeClassifier
RandomForestClassifier
XGBClassifier

The techniques to explore are the oversampling and undersampling, besides the algoriths 'Balanced Bagging Classifier' and 'Easy Ensemble Classifier' as hybrid methodos.

The algortihs selected will be created with the differents X_train and y_train created and then will be ranked.

In [7]:
def plot_sampling(X, y, X_res, y_res, ax, fig = None, sampler = None, title=None):
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.set_palette(SETCOL1)
    if fig:
        ax[0].scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, alpha=0.8, edgecolor="g")
        ax[1].scatter(X_res[:, 0], X_res[:, 1], c=y_res, alpha=0.8, edgecolor="g")
        sns.despine(fig)
        ax[0].set_title(f"Before sampling")
        if sampler:
            ax[1].set_title(f"Resampling with {sampler.__class__.__name__}")
        else:
            ax[1].set_title("After sampling")
    else:
        print('pass the `fig` parameter')

Oversampling

There are several methods available, but I am going to test some of them, and the first one that I decided to apply is the most common data augmentation technique is known as Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique or SMOTE for short. I applied this technique before and I got descent results. I think is a good method and popular one because it looks to balancing the class distribution and take care on creating overfitting of the majority class by creating larger and less specific decision regions.

In [10]:
X_oversample, y_oversample = SMOTE().fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
In [11]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (18,6))
plot_sampling(X_train, y_train, X_oversample, y_oversample, ax, fig, sampler = SMOTE())

Undersample

Another aproach worthy to explore is the undersample, even if the dataset is only 30K samples. In this approach, we reduce the number of samples from the majority class to match the number of samples in the minority class. It might performs poorly than the oversampling, but could give me a ranges to evaluate models.

In [12]:
nm2 = NearMiss(version=2)
X_undersample, y_undersample = nm2.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
In [13]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (18,6))
plot_sampling(X_train, y_train, X_undersample, y_undersample, ax, fig, sampler=NearMiss(version=2))

#======================================

def showing_results(y_train, y_test, y_pred_test, y_pred_train):
    conf_matrix_test = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_test)
    conf_matrix_train = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_pred_train)
    print('Confusion Matrix: Test')
    print('\n')
    print (conf_matrix_test)
    print('\n')
    print('Classification Report: Test')
    print('\n')
    print (classification_report(y_test, y_pred_test))
    
    print('Confusion Matrix: Train')
    print('\n')
    print (conf_matrix_train)
    print('\n')
    print('Classification Report: Test')
    print('\n')
    print (classification_report(y_train, y_pred_train))

%%time
evaluacion = list()
for i, m in clasificadores.items():
    print ('EVALUANDO MODELO: {model}'.format(model=i))
    model = {}
    model['name'] = i
    y_pred_train = m.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_val = m.predict(X_val)
    y_prob_train = m.predict_proba(X_train)
    y_prob_val = m.predict_proba(X_val)
        
    model['accuracy_train'] = accuracy_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=y_pred_train)
    model['accuracy_vals'] = accuracy_score(y_true=y_val, y_pred=y_pred_val)
    model['precision_train'] = precision_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=y_pred_train)
    model['precision_vals'] = precision_score(y_true=y_val, y_pred=y_pred_val)
    model['recall_train'] = recall_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=y_pred_train)
    model['recall_vals'] = recall_score(y_true=y_val, y_pred=y_pred_val)
    model['f1_train'] = f1_score(y_true=y_train, y_pred=y_pred_train)
    model['f1_vals'] = f1_score(y_true=y_val, y_pred=y_pred_val)
    model['AUC_train'] = roc_auc_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    model['AUC_val'] = roc_auc_score(y_val, y_pred_val)
    evaluacion.append(model)

%%time
# Calculamos AUC y las matrices de confusin
msc = list()
for k, v in clasificadores.items():
    print("\n----------------------------------------------------------------")
    print ('Obteniendo AUC de: {model}'.format(model=k))
    model = {}
    model['name'] = k
    y_pred_val = v.predict(X_val)
    y_pred_train = v.predict(X_train)
    #======================================
    print('\n')
    roc_auc_train = roc_auc_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    print(f"AUC_train: {roc_auc_train:.2f}")
    roc_auc_val = roc_auc_score(y_val, y_pred_val)
    print(f"AUC_val: {roc_auc_val:.2f}")
    print('\n')
    #======================================
    y_probas_train = v.predict_proba(X_train)
    preds_probtrain = y_probas_train [:,1]
    y_probas_val = v.predict_proba(X_val)
    preds_probval = y_probas_val [:,1]
    #======================================
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.set_palette("Set2")
    #print("\n----------------------------------------------------------------")
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=[14, 8])
    sns.set(font_scale=1.1)
    skplt.metrics.plot_roc_curve(y_val, y_probas_val, ax=ax1)
    skplt.metrics.plot_roc_curve(y_train, y_probas_train, ax=ax2)
    plt.show()
    #======================================
    conf_matrixval = confusion_matrix(y_val, y_pred_val)
    conf_matrixtrain = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_pred_train)
    model['conf_matrixvalnorm'] = (conf_matrixval/(sum(conf_matrixval)))*100
    model['conf_matrixtrainnorm'] = (conf_matrixtrain/(sum(conf_matrixtrain)))*100

    msc.append(model)

%%time

def plot_importance(model):
    importance = pandas.DataFrame({
        "feature": feature_names,
        "importance": model.feature_importances_
    }).sort_values("importance", ascending = False)

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 35))
    sns.set(font_scale=1.3)
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.barplot(y = "feature", x = "importance", data = importance, alpha = 0.6, palette = "Set2")
    plt.show()
    
for k, v in clasificadores.items():

    model = {}
    model['name'] = k
    if k == 'LogisticReg' or k == 'LogisticReg osamplig' or k == 'LogisticReg usamplig' or k == 'Stochastic Gradient Descent' \
        or k == 'Stochastic Gradient Descent osamplig' or k == 'Stochastic Gradient Descent usamplig' \
        or k == 'BalancedBaggingClassifier' or  k == 'EasyEnsembleClassifier':
        continue
    
    print("\n----------------------------------------------------------------")
    print ('Getting Variable_Importance from: {model}'.format(model=k))
    plot_importance(v)

Observations:¶

After running the model's set selected on this phase and exploring different tecniques, here some general comments on the model:

  • Undersamplig method performce the worst as expected.
  • There is not too much variation between the results on the original input and the oversampling method.
  • The Random Forest algorithm has a considering impreve on AUC for the train 0.61 to 0.82, I must mention that the hyper parameter were a bit different than in the first approach, however I don't like the difference between the AUC_train: 0.82 and AUC_val: 0.62.
  • Regarding F1 score, Logistic Regresion perform better than the other models by getting f1_train: 0.34 and f1_val:0.36. The AUC_train was 0.60 and AUC_val 0.63.
  • The XGBoost, gave AUC_train 0.63 and AUC_val: 0.55, and f1_train:0.42 and f1_val: 0.21. However, looking at the coffisuon matrix, got the best results TP:871% , FP: 9.2% , FN:12.9%, TN:90.8%. However, accuracy is not appropriate when the data is imbalanced. Because the model can achieve higher accuracy by just predicting accurately the majority class while performing poorly on the minority class which in most cases is the class we care about the most.
    • Regarding the dataset conditions, I am going to select this three models for the next step, considering as a best option the Logistic Regresion, because has the most consistent realists regarding difference between train and val. The second option is the Random Forest, because has the best F1 score.
